stories: Optical neural networks (ONNs) have the potential for high-speed, high-throughput, and low-energy computing. In conventional ONNs, only light amplitudes are modulated at the input and detected at the output, while the light phases are still ignored. To address this issue, we propose a framework called OplixNet to compress the areas of ONNs by modulating input image data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. The input and output parts of the ONNs are redesigned to make full use of both amplitude and phase information. Mutual learning across different ONN structures is introduced to maintain the accuracy. Experimental results demonstrate that the proposed framework significantly reduces the areas of ONNs with the accuracy within an acceptable range. For example, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33% accuracy decrease on fully connected neural network (FCNN) and 74.88% area is reduced with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on ResNet-32.

Optical neural networks (ONNs) have the potential to perform high-speed, high-throughput, and low-energy computing. However, in traditional ONNs, only the light amplitudes are modulated at the input and detected at the output, while the light phases are still ignored. To address this issue, we propose a framework called OplixNet, which can compress the areas of ONNs by modulating input image data into both the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. The input and output parts of the ONNs are redesigned to make full use of both amplitude and phase information. Mutual learning across different ONN structures is introduced to maintain the accuracy. Experimental results show that the proposed framework can significantly reduce the areas of ONNs with the accuracy within an acceptable range. For example, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33% accuracy decrease on fully connected neural network (FCNN) and 74.88% area is reduced with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on ResNet-32.

Traditional optical neural networks (ONNs) only modulate input data into the light amplitudes, but the light phases are still ignored. This limits the potential of ONNs to perform high-speed, high-throughput, and low-energy computing. To address this issue, we propose a framework called OplixNet, which can compress the areas of ONNs by modulating input image data into both the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. The input and output parts of the ONNs are redesigned to make full use of both amplitude and phase information. Mutual learning across different ONN structures is introduced to maintain the accuracy. Experimental results show that the proposed framework can significantly reduce the areas of ONNs with the accuracy within an acceptable range. For example, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33% accuracy decrease on fully connected neural network (FCNN) and 74.88% area is reduced with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on ResNet-32.

Traditional optical neural networks (ONNs) only utilize light amplitude modulation for input data, neglecting the potential of light phase information. To address this limitation, we introduce OplixNet, a framework that encodes input image data into both light amplitude and phase parts. We redesign the input and output parts of ONNs to fully utilize both types of information. Mutual learning is employed across different ONN structures to maintain accuracy. Experimental results show that OplixNet can significantly reduce the areas of ONNs with a small impact on accuracy. For example, 75.03% area reduction with 0.33% accuracy decrease on FCNN, and 74.88% area reduction with 2.38% accuracy decrease on ResNet-32.
